solution:
Note that $\arg \left( \frac{w - z}{z} \right) = \arg \left( \frac{w}{z} - 1 \right).$  Thus, we can rotate $z$ and $w,$ and assume that $z = 10.$  Then
\[\arg \left( \frac{w - z}{z} \right) = \arg \left( \frac{w - 10}{10} \right) = \arg (w - 10).\]Since $|w| = 1,$ the set of complex numbers of the form $w - 10$ is the circle centered at $-10$ with radius 1.

Identify $A$ with the complex number $-10,$ identify $W$ with the complex number $w,$ let $O$ be the origin.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, O, W;

A = (-5,0);
O = (0,0);
W = (-24/5,2*sqrt(6)/5);

draw((-7,0)--(1,0));
draw((0,-1)--(0,1));
draw(Circle(A,1));
draw(A--W--O);
draw(rightanglemark(A,W,O,6));

label("$O$", O, SE);
label("$W$", W, N);

dot("$A$", A, S);
[/asy]

Then $\tan^2 \theta = \tan^2 \angle AOW.$  We see that $\tan^2 \angle AOW$ is maximized when $\angle AOW$ is maximized, which occurs when $\overline{OW}$ is tangent to the circle.  In this case, $\angle AWO = 90^\circ,$ so by Pythagoras, $OW = \sqrt{99},$ and $\tan \angle AOW = \frac{1}{\sqrt{99}},$ so
\[\tan^2 \angle AOW = \boxed{\frac{1}{99}}.\]
